[src:pandoc/demos] You can try pandoc in your browser at https://pandoc.org/app.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] This document is for people who are unfamiliar with command line tools.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Command-line experts can go straight to the User’s Guide or the pandoc man page.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] First, install pandoc, following the instructions for your platform.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You should now see a rectangle with a “prompt” (possibly just a symbol like `%`, but probably including more information, such as your username and directory), and a blinking cursor.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You should see a message telling you which version of pandoc is installed, and giving you some additional information.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Your terminal should print your current working directory.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] (Guess what `pwd` stands for?) This should be your home directory.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You should be in the `Documents` subdirectory of your home directory.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Go back to your `Documents` directory if you’re not there already.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] OK, that’s all you need to know for now about using the terminal.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] But here’s a secret that will save you a lot of typing.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You can always type the up-arrow key to go back through your history of commands.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] So if you want to use a command you typed earlier, you don’t need to type it again: just use up-arrow until it comes up.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] (You can use down-arrow as well, to go the other direction.) Once you have the command, you can also use the left and right arrows and the backspace/delete key to edit it.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Most terminals also support tab completion of directories and filenames.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Your terminal should fill in the rest (`test`), and then you can hit enter.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You should see the cursor just sitting there, waiting for you to type something.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] When you’re finished (the cursor should be at the beginning of the line), type `Ctrl-D` on OS X or Linux, or `Ctrl-Z` followed by `Enter` on Windows.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You should now see your text converted to HTML!
[src:pandoc/getting-started] When pandoc is invoked without specifying any input files, it operates as a “filter,” taking input from the terminal and sending its output back to the terminal.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You can use this feature to play around with pandoc.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] By default, input is interpreted as pandoc markdown, and output is HTML.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] and hit `Ctrl-D` (or `Ctrl-Z` followed by `Enter` on Windows).
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Now try converting something from markdown to LaTeX.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] What command do you think you should use?
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You’ll probably want to use pandoc to convert a file, not to read text from the terminal.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] That’s easy, but first we need to create a text file in our `pandoc-test` subdirectory.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Now save your file as `test1.md` in the directory `Documents/pandoc-test`.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Note: If you use plain text a lot, you’ll want a better editor than `Notepad` or `TextEdit`.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You might want to look at Visual Studio Code or Sublime Text or (if you’re willing to put in some time learning an unfamiliar interface) Vim or Emacs.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] We should still be in the `Documents/pandoc-test` directory.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] This will list the files in the current directory.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You should see the file you created, `test1.md`.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] The filename `test1.md` tells pandoc which file to convert.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] The `-s` option says to create a “standalone” file, with a header and footer, not just a fragment.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] And the `-o test1.html` says to put the output in the file `test1.html`.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Note that we could have omitted `-f markdown` and `-t html`, since the default is to convert from markdown to HTML, but it doesn’t hurt to include them.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Check that the file was created by typing `ls` again.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] You should see a browser window with your document.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Try opening `test1.tex` in your text editor.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Pandoc can often figure out the input and output formats from the filename extensions.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Pandoc knows you’re trying to create a LaTeX document, because of the `.tex` extension.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Now try creating a Word document (with extension `docx`).
[src:pandoc/getting-started] If you want to create a PDF, you’ll need to have LaTeX installed.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] At this point you can start to learn more about them by reading the User’s Guide.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] The `--mathml` option causes pandoc to convert TeX math into MathML.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] Now try the same thing without `--mathml`.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] to get a list of all the supported options.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] All of this information is also in the User’s Guide.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] If you get stuck, you can always ask questions on the discussion forum.
[src:pandoc/getting-started] But be sure to check the FAQs first, and search through the forum to see if your question has been answered before.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] A **lightweight markup language** (**LML**), also termed a **simple** or **humane markup language**, is a markup language with simple, unobtrusive syntax.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] It is designed to be easy to write using any generic text editor and easy to read in its raw form.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] It is used in applications where it may be necessary to read the raw document and the final rendered output.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] For instance, a person downloading a software library might prefer to read the documentation in a text editor rather than a web browser.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Another use for such languages is to provide for data entry in web-based publishing, as in blogs and wikis, where the input interface is a simple text box.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] The server software then converts the input into a common document markup language like HTML.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Lightweight markup languages were originally used on text-only displays which could not display characters in italics or bold, so informal methods to convey this information had to be developed.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] This formatting choice was naturally carried forth to plain-text email communications.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Console browsers may also resort to similar display conventions.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] In 1986 international standard SGML provided facilities to define and parse lightweight markup languages using grammars and tag implication.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] The 1998 W3C XML is a profile of SGML that omits these facilities.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] However, no SGML document type definition (DTD) for any of the languages listed below is known.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Lightweight markup languages can be categorized by their tag types.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages distinguish between markup for lines or blocks and for shorter spans of texts, but some only support inline markup.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Some markup languages are tailored for a specific purpose, such as documenting computer code (e.g., POD, reST, RD) or being converted to a certain output format (usually HTML or LaTeX) and nothing else, others are more general in application.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] This includes whether they are oriented on textual presentation or on data serialization.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Presentation oriented languages include AsciiDoc, atx, BBCode, Creole, Crossmark, Djot, Epytext, Haml, JsonML, MakeDoc, Markdown, Org-mode, POD (Perl), reST (Python), RD (Ruby), Setext, SiSU, SPIP, Xupl, Texy!, Textile, txt2tags, UDO and Wikitext.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Data serialization oriented languages include Curl (homoiconic, but also reads JSON; every object serializes), JSON, and YAML.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Markdown's own syntax does not support class attributes or id attributes; however, since Markdown supports the inclusion of native HTML code, these features can be implemented using direct HTML.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] txt2tags' own syntax does not support class attributes or id attributes; however, since txt2tags supports inclusion of native HTML code in tagged areas, these features can be implemented using direct HTML when saving to an HTML target.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki does not support HTML import natively, but HTML to DokuWiki converters and importers exist and are mentioned in the official documentation.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki does not support class or id attributes, but can be set up to support HTML code, which does support both features.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] HTML code support was built-in before release 2023-04-04.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] In later versions, HTML code support can be achieved through plug-ins, though it is discouraged.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Although usually documented as yielding italic and bold text, most lightweight markup processors output semantic HTML elements `em` and `strong` instead.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Monospaced text may either result in semantic `code` or presentational `tt` elements.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Few languages make a distinction, e.g., Textile, or allow the user to configure the output easily, e.g., Texy.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] LMLs sometimes differ for multi-word markup where some require the markup characters to replace the inter-word spaces (*infix*).
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Some languages require one character as prefix and suffix, others need two or even three, or support both with slightly different meaning, e.g., different levels of emphasis.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Gemtext does not have any inline formatting, monospaced text (called preformatted text in the context of Gemtext) must have the opening and closing ``` on their own lines.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] In HTML, text is emphasized with the `<em>` and `<strong>` element types, whereas `<i>` and `<b>` traditionally mark up text to be italicized or bold-faced, respectively.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word and Outlook, and accordingly other word processors and mail clients that strive for a similar user experience, support the basic convention of using asterisks for boldface and underscores for italic style.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] While Word removes the characters, Outlook retains them.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] In HTML, removed or deleted and inserted text is marked up with the `<del>` and `<ins>` element types, respectively.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] However, legacy element types `<s>` or `<strike>` and `<u>` are still also available for stricken and underlined spans of text.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] AsciiDoc, ATX, Creole, MediaWiki, PmWiki, reST, Slack, Textile and WhatsApp do not support dedicated markup for underlining text.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Textile does, however, support insertion via the `+inserted+` syntax.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] ATX, Creole, MediaWiki, PmWiki, reST and Setext do not support dedicated markup for striking through text.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki supports HTML-like `<del>stricken</del>` syntax, even with embedded HTML disabled.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] AsciiDoc supports stricken text through a built-in *text span* prefix: `[.line-through]#stricken#`.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Quoted computer code is traditionally presented in typewriter-like fonts where each character occupies the same fixed width.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] HTML offers the semantic `<code>` and the deprecated, presentational `<tt>` element types for this task.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] The second style is based on repeated markers (e.g., hash `#`, equals `=` or asterisk `*`) at the start of the heading itself, where the number of repetitions indicates the (sometimes inverse) heading level.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages also support the reduplication of the markers at the end of the line, but whereas some make them mandatory, others do not even expect their numbers to match.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Org-mode supports indentation as a means of indicating the level.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] BBCode does not support section headings at all.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] POD and Textile choose the HTML convention of numbered heading levels instead.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word supports auto-formatting paragraphs as headings if they do not contain more than a handful of words, no period at the end and the user hits the enter key twice.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] For lower levels, the user may press the tabulator key the according number of times before entering the text, i.e., one through eight tabs for heading levels two through nine.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Hyperlinks can either be added inline, which may clutter the code because of long URLs, or with named `alias` or numbered `id` references to lines containing nothing but the address and related attributes and often may be located anywhere in the document.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages allow the author to specify text `Text` to be displayed instead of the plain address `http://example.com` and some also provide methods to set a different link title `Title` which may contain more information about the destination.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] LMLs that are tailored for special setups, e.g., wikis or code documentation, may automatically generate named anchors (for headings, functions etc.) inside the document, link to related pages (possibly in a different namespace) or provide a textual search for linked keywords.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages employ (double) square or angular brackets to surround links, but hardly any two languages are completely compatible.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Many can automatically recognize and parse absolute URLs inside the text without further markup.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Gemtext and setext links must be on a line by themselves, they cannot be used inline.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Org-mode's normal link syntax does a text search of the file.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] You can also put in dedicated targets with `<<id>>`.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] HTML requires an explicit element for the list, specifying its type, and one for each list item, but most lightweight markup languages need only different line prefixes for the bullet points or enumerated items.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Some languages rely on indentation for nested lists, others use repeated parent list markers.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word automatically converts paragraphs that start with an asterisk `*`, hyphen-minus `-` or greater-than bracket `>` followed by a space or horizontal tabulator as bullet list items.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Languages differ on whether they support optional or mandatory digits in numbered list items, which kinds of enumerators they understand (e.g., decimal digit *1*, roman numerals *i* or *I*, alphabetic letters *a* or *A*) and whether they support to keep explicit values in the output format.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Some Markdown dialects, for instance, will respect a start value other than 1, but ignore any other explicit value.
[src:pandoc/lightweight-markup-language] Slack assists the user in entering enumerated and bullet lists, but does not actually format them as such, i.e., it just includes a leading digit followed by a period and a space or a bullet character `•` in front of a line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Pandoc is a Haskell library for converting from one markup format to another, and a command-line tool that uses this library.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Pandoc can convert between numerous markup and word processing formats, including, but not limited to, various flavors of Markdown, HTML, LaTeX and Word docx.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For the full lists of input and output formats, see the `--from` and `--to` options below.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Pandoc can also produce PDF output: see creating a PDF, below.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Pandoc’s enhanced version of Markdown includes syntax for tables, definition lists, metadata blocks, footnotes, citations, math, and much more.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Pandoc has a modular design: it consists of a set of readers, which parse text in a given format and produce a native representation of the document (an *abstract syntax tree* or AST), and a set of writers, which convert this native representation into a target format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Thus, adding an input or output format requires only adding a reader or writer.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Users can also run custom pandoc filters to modify the intermediate AST.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Because pandoc’s intermediate representation of a document is less expressive than many of the formats it converts between, one should not expect perfect conversions between every format and every other.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Pandoc attempts to preserve the structural elements of a document, but not formatting details such as margin size.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] And some document elements, such as complex tables, may not fit into pandoc’s simple document model.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] While conversions from pandoc’s Markdown to all formats aspire to be perfect, conversions from formats more expressive than pandoc’s Markdown can be expected to be lossy.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If no *input-files* are specified, input is read from *stdin*.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] By default, pandoc produces a document fragment.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For more information on how standalone documents are produced, see Templates below.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If multiple input files are given, pandoc will concatenate them all (with blank lines between them) before parsing.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The format of the input and output can be specified explicitly using command-line options.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The input format can be specified using the `-f/--from` option, the output format using the `-t/--to` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Supported input and output formats are listed below under Options (see `-f` for input formats and `-t` for output formats).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] You can also use `pandoc --list-input-formats` and `pandoc --list-output-formats` to print lists of supported formats.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If the input or output format is not specified explicitly, pandoc will attempt to guess it from the extensions of the filenames.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] will convert `hello.txt` from Markdown to LaTeX.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If no output file is specified (so that output goes to *stdout*), or if the output file’s extension is unknown, the output format will default to HTML.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If no input file is specified (so that input comes from *stdin*), or if the input files’ extensions are unknown, the input format will be assumed to be Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Pandoc uses the UTF-8 character encoding for both input and output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note that in some output formats (such as HTML, LaTeX, ConTeXt, RTF, OPML, DocBook, and Texinfo), information about the character encoding is included in the document header, which will only be included if you use the `-s/--standalone` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] By default, pandoc will use LaTeX to create the PDF, which requires that a LaTeX engine be installed (see `--pdf-engine` below).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Alternatively, pandoc can use ConTeXt, roff ms, or HTML as an intermediate format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] To do this, specify an output file with a `.pdf` extension, as before, but add the `--pdf-engine` option or `-t context`, `-t html`, or `-t ms` to the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The tool used to generate the PDF from the intermediate format may be specified using `--pdf-engine`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] You can control the PDF style using variables, depending on the intermediate format used: see variables for LaTeX, variables for ConTeXt, variables for `wkhtmltopdf`, variables for ms.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] When HTML is used as an intermediate format, the output can be styled using `--css`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] To debug the PDF creation, it can be useful to look at the intermediate representation: instead of `-o test.pdf`, use for example `-s -o test.tex` to output the generated LaTeX.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] You can then test it with `pdflatex test.tex`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If `CJKmainfont` is set, `xeCJK` is needed if `xelatex` is used, else `luatexja` is needed if `lualatex` is used.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `framed` is required if code is highlighted in a scheme that use a colored background.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The use of `xelatex` or `lualatex` as the PDF engine requires `fontspec`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `lualatex` uses `selnolig` and `lua-ul`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `xelatex` uses `bidi` (with the `dir` variable set).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If the `mathspec` variable is set, `xelatex` will use `mathspec` instead of `unicode-math`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The `csquotes` package will be used for typography if the `csquotes` variable or metadata field is set to a true value.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The `natbib`, `biblatex`, `bibtex`, and `biber` packages can optionally be used for citation rendering.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If math with `\cancel`, `\bcancel`, or `\xcancel` is used, the `cancel` package is needed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Instead of an input file, an absolute URI may be given.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Extensions can be individually enabled or disabled by appending `+EXTENSION` or `-EXTENSION` to the format name.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] See Extensions below, for a list of extensions and their names.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] See `--list-input-formats` and `--list-extensions`, below.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note that `odt`, `docx`, `epub`, and `pdf` output will not be directed to *stdout* unless forced with `-o -`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] See `--list-output-formats` and `--list-extensions`, below.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Write output to *FILE* instead of *stdout*.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If *FILE* is `-`, output will go to *stdout*, even if a non-textual format (`docx`, `odt`, `epub2`, `epub3`) is specified.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If the output format is `chunkedhtml` and *FILE* has no extension, then instead of producing a `.zip` file pandoc will create a directory *FILE* and unpack the zip archive there (unless *FILE* already exists, in which case an error will be raised).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specify the user data directory to search for pandoc data files.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If this option is not specified, the default user data directory will be used.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] On *nix and macOS systems this will be the `pandoc` subdirectory of the XDG data directory (by default, `$HOME/.local/share`, overridable by setting the `XDG_DATA_HOME` environment variable).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If that directory does not exist and `$HOME/.pandoc` exists, it will be used (for backwards compatibility).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] On Windows the default user data directory is `%APPDATA%\pandoc`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] You can find the default user data directory on your system by looking at the output of `pandoc --version`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Data files placed in this directory (for example, `reference.odt`, `reference.docx`, `epub.css`, `templates`) will override pandoc’s normal defaults.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specify a set of default option settings.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] *FILE* is a YAML or JSON file whose fields correspond to command-line option settings.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] All options for document conversion, including input and output files, can be set using a defaults file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The file will be searched for first in the working directory, and then in the `defaults` subdirectory of the user data directory (see `--data-dir`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The `.yaml` extension will be added if *FILE* lacs an extension.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] See the section Defaults files for more information on the file format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Settings from the defaults file may be overridden or extended by subsequent options on the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Run pandoc in a sandbox, limiting IO operations in readers and writers to reading the files specified on the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note that this option does not limit IO operations by filters or in the production of PDF documents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] But it does offer security against, for example, disclosure of files through the use of `include` directives.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Anyone using pandoc on untrusted user input should use this option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note: some readers and writers (e.g., `docx`) need access to data files.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If these are stored on the file system, then pandoc will not be able to find them when run in `--sandbox` mode and will raise an error.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For these applications, we recommend using a pandoc binary compiled with the `embed_data_files` option, which causes the data files to be baked into the binary instead of being stored on the file system.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Exit with error status if there are any warnings.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Write log messages in machine-readable JSON format to *FILE*.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] All messages above DEBUG level will be written, regardless of verbosity settings (`--verbose`, `--quiet`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] List supported input formats, one per line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] List supported output formats, one per line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] List supported extensions for *FORMAT*, one per line, preceded by a `+` or `-` indicating whether it is enabled by default in *FORMAT*.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If *FORMAT* is not specified, defaults for pandoc’s Markdown are given.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] List supported languages for syntax highlighting, one per line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] List supported styles for syntax highlighting, one per line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Shift heading levels by a positive or negative integer.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For example, with `--shift-heading-level-by=-1`, level 2 headings become level 1 headings, and level 3 headings become level 2 headings.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Headings cannot have a level less than 1, so a heading that would be shifted below level 1 becomes a regular paragraph.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Exception: with a shift of -N, a level-N heading at the beginning of the document replaces the metadata title.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `--shift-heading-level-by=-1` is a good choice when converting HTML or Markdown documents that use an initial level-1 heading for the document title and level-2+ headings for sections.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `--shift-heading-level-by=1` may be a good choice for converting Markdown documents that use level-1 headings for sections to HTML, since pandoc uses a level-1 heading to render the document title.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specify classes to use for indented code blocks—for example, `perl,numberLines` or `haskell`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Multiple classes may be separated by spaces or commas.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specify a default extension to use when image paths/URLs have no extension.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This allows you to use the same source for formats that require different kinds of images.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Currently this option only affects the Markdown and LaTeX readers.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Parse each file individually before combining for multifile documents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This will allow footnotes in different files with the same identifiers to work as expected.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If this option is set, footnotes and links will not work across files.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Reading binary files (docx, odt, epub) implies `--file-scope`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If two or more files are processed using `--file-scope`, prefixes based on the filenames will be added to identifiers in order to disambiguate them, and internal links will be adjusted accordingly.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For example, a header with identifier `foo` in `subdir/file1.txt` will have its identifier changed to `subdir__file1.txt__foo`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specify an executable to be used as a filter transforming the pandoc AST after the input is parsed and before the output is written.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The executable should read JSON from stdin and write JSON to stdout.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The JSON must be formatted like pandoc’s own JSON input and output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The name of the output format will be passed to the filter as the first argument.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The latter form may be useful for debugging filters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `Text.Pandoc.JSON` exports `toJSONFilter` to facilitate writing filters in Haskell.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Those who would prefer to write filters in python can use the module `pandocfilters`, installable from PyPI.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] There are also pandoc filter libraries in PHP, perl, and JavaScript/node.js.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Filters, Lua-filters, and citeproc processing are applied in the order specified on the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Transform the document in a similar fashion as JSON filters (see `--filter`), but use pandoc’s built-in Lua filtering system.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The given Lua script is expected to return a list of Lua filters which will be applied in order.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Each Lua filter must contain element-transforming functions indexed by the name of the AST element on which the filter function should be applied.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The `pandoc` Lua module provides helper functions for element creation.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] It is always loaded into the script’s Lua environment.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] See the Lua filters documentation for further details.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `$DATADIR/filters` where `$DATADIR` is the user data directory (see `--data-dir`, above).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Filters, Lua filters, and citeproc processing are applied in the order specified on the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Set the metadata field *KEY* to the value *VAL*.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] A value specified on the command line overrides a value specified in the document using YAML metadata blocks.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Values will be parsed as YAML boolean or string values.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If no value is specified, the value will be treated as Boolean true.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Like `--variable`, `--metadata` causes template variables to be set.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] But unlike `--variable`, `--metadata` affects the metadata of the underlying document (which is accessible from filters and may be printed in some output formats) and metadata values will be escaped when inserted into the template.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Read metadata from the supplied YAML (or JSON) file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option can be used with every input format, but string scalars in the metadata file will always be parsed as Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Metadata values specified inside the document, or by using `-M`, overwrite values specified with this option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The file will be searched for first in the working directory, and then in the `metadata` subdirectory of the user data directory (see `--data-dir`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Preserve tabs instead of converting them to spaces.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] (By default, pandoc converts tabs to spaces before parsing its input.) Note that this will only affect tabs in literal code spans and code blocks.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Tabs in regular text are always treated as spaces.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specify the number of spaces per tab (default is 4).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specifies what to do with insertions, deletions, and comments produced by the MS Word “Track Changes” feature.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `accept` (the default) processes all the insertions and deletions.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Both `accept` and `reject` ignore comments.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `all` includes all insertions, deletions, and comments, wrapped in spans with `insertion`, `deletion`, `comment-start`, and `comment-end` classes, respectively.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The author and time of change is included.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] `all` is useful for scripting: only accepting changes from a certain reviewer, say, or before a certain date.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If a paragraph is inserted or deleted, `track-changes=all` produces a span with the class `paragraph-insertion`/`paragraph-deletion` before the affected paragraph break.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option only affects the docx reader.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Extract images and other media contained in or linked from the source document to the path *DIR*, creating it if necessary, and adjust the images references in the document so they point to the extracted files.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Media are downloaded, read from the file system, or extracted from a binary container (e.g. docx), as needed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The original file paths are used if they are relative paths not containing `..`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Otherwise filenames are constructed from the SHA1 hash of the contents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If the path given ends in `.zip`, then instead of creating a directory, pandoc will create a zip archive containing the media files.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specifies a custom abbreviations file, with abbreviations one to a line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If this option is not specified, pandoc will read the data file `abbreviations` from the user data directory or fall back on a system default.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] To see the system default, use `pandoc --print-default-data-file=abbreviations`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The only use pandoc makes of this list is in the Markdown reader.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Strings found in this list will be followed by a nonbreaking space, and the period will not produce sentence-ending space in formats like LaTeX.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Set a parameter value that will be made available to the typst parser in `sys.inputs`, like `--input` in the `typst` CLI.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Either `:` or `=` may be used to separate *KEY* from *VAL*.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Values containing spaces must be quoted.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Print diagnostic output tracing parser progress to stderr.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option is intended for use by developers in diagnosing performance issues.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Produce output with an appropriate header and footer (e.g. a standalone HTML, LaTeX, TEI, or RTF file, not a fragment).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option is set automatically for `pdf`, `epub`, `epub3`, `fb2`, `docx`, and `odt` output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For `native` output, this option causes metadata to be included; otherwise, metadata is suppressed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Use the specified file as a custom template for the generated document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] See Templates, below, for a description of template syntax.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If the template is not found, pandoc will search for it in the `templates` subdirectory of the user data directory (see `--data-dir`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If no extension is specified and an extensionless template is not found, pandoc will look for a template with an extension corresponding to the writer, so that `--template=special` looks for `special.html` for HTML output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If this option is not used, a default template appropriate for the output format will be used (see `-D/--print-default-template`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Set the template variable *KEY* to the string value *VAL* when rendering the document in standalone mode.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If no *VAL* is specified, the key will be given the value `true`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Structured values (lists, maps) cannot be assigned using this option, but they can be assigned in the `variables` section of a defaults file or using the `--variable-json` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If the variable already has a *list* value, the value will be added to the list.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If it already has another kind of value, it will be made into a list containing the previous and the new value.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For example, `-V author=Joe -V author=Sue` makes `author` contain a list of strings: `Joe` and `Sue`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Set the template variable *KEY* to the value specified by a JSON string (this may be a boolean, a string, a list, or a mapping; a number will be treated as a string).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For example, `--variable-json foo=false` will give `foo` the boolean false value, while `--variable-json foo='"false"'` will give it the string value `"false"`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If the variable already has a value, this value will be replaced.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Print the system default template for an output *FORMAT*.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] (See `-t` for a list of possible *FORMAT*s.) Templates in the user data directory are ignored.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option may be used with `-o`/`--output` to redirect output to a file, but `-o`/`--output` must come before `--print-default-template` on the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note that some of the default templates use partials, for example `styles.html`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] To print the partials, use `--print-default-data-file`: for example, `--print-default-data-file=templates/styles.html`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Files in the user data directory are ignored.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option may be used with `-o`/`--output` to redirect output to a file, but `-o`/`--output` must come before `--print-default-data-file` on the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Manually specify line endings: `crlf` (Windows), `lf` (macOS/Linux/UNIX), or `native` (line endings appropriate to the OS on which pandoc is being run).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specify the default dpi (dots per inch) value for conversion from pixels to inch/centimeters and vice versa.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] (Technically, the correct term would be ppi: pixels per inch.) The default is 96dpi.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] When images contain information about dpi internally, the encoded value is used instead of the default specified by this option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Determine how text is wrapped in the output (the source code, not the rendered version).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] With `auto` (the default), pandoc will attempt to wrap lines to the column width specified by `--columns` (default 72).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] With `none`, pandoc will not wrap lines at all.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] With `preserve`, pandoc will attempt to preserve the wrapping from the source document (that is, where there are nonsemantic newlines in the source, there will be nonsemantic newlines in the output as well).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] In `ipynb` output, this option affects wrapping of the contents of Markdown cells.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This affects text wrapping in the generated source code (see `--wrap`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] It also affects calculation of column widths for plain text tables (see Tables below).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Include an automatically generated table of contents (or, in the case of `latex`, `context`, `docx`, `odt`, `opendocument`, `rst`, or `ms`, an instruction to create one) in the output document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option has no effect unless `-s/--standalone` is used, and it has no effect on `man`, `docbook4`, `docbook5`, or `jats` output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note that if you are producing a PDF via `ms` and using (the default) `groff` as a `--pdf-engine`, the table of contents will appear at the end of the document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If you would prefer it to be at the beginning of the document, before the title, you can use `--pdf-engine=pdfroff`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specify the number of section levels to include in the table of contents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The default is 3 (which means that level-1, 2, and 3 headings will be listed in the contents).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Include an automatically generated list of figures (or, in some formats, an instruction to create one) in the output document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option has no effect unless `-s/--standalone` is used, and it only has an effect on `latex`, `context`, and `docx` output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Include an automatically generated list of tables (or, in some formats, an instruction to create one) in the output document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Strip out HTML comments in the Markdown or Textile source, rather than passing them on to Markdown, Textile or HTML output as raw HTML.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This does not apply to HTML comments inside raw HTML blocks when the `markdown_in_html_blocks` extension is not set.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The method to use for code syntax highlighting.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Setting a specific *STYLE* causes highlighting to be performed with the internal highlighting engine, using KDE syntax definitions and styles.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The `idiomatic` method uses a format-specific highlighter if one is available, or the default style if the target format has no idiomatic highlighting method.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Setting this option to `none` disables all syntax highlighting.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The `default` method uses a format-specific default.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The default for HTML, EPUB, Docx, Ms, Man, and LaTeX output is to use the internal highlighter with the default style; for Typst it is to use Typst’s own syntax highlighting system.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Style options are `pygments` (the default), `kate`, `monochrome`, `breezeDark`, `espresso`, `zenburn`, `haddock`, and `tango`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For more information on syntax highlighting in pandoc, see Syntax highlighting, below.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Instead of a *STYLE* name, a JSON file with extension `.theme` may be supplied.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This will be parsed as a KDE syntax highlighting theme and (if valid) used as the highlighting style.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] To generate the JSON version of an existing style, use `--print-highlight-style`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Disables syntax highlighting for code blocks and inlines, even when a language attribute is given.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Specifies the coloring style to be used in highlighted source code.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Prints a JSON version of a highlighting style, which can be modified, saved with a `.theme` extension, and used with `--syntax-highlighting`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option may be used with `-o`/`--output` to redirect output to a file, but `-o`/`--output` must come before `--print-highlight-style` on the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Instructs pandoc to load a KDE XML syntax definition file, which will be used for syntax highlighting of appropriately marked code blocks.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This can be used to add support for new languages or to use altered syntax definitions for existing languages.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option may be repeated to add multiple syntax definitions.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Include contents of *FILE*, verbatim, at the end of the header.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This can be used, for example, to include special CSS or JavaScript in HTML documents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option can be used repeatedly to include multiple files in the header.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] They will be included in the order specified.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Include contents of *FILE*, verbatim, at the beginning of the document body (e.g. after the `<body>` tag in HTML, or the `\begin{document}` command in LaTeX).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This can be used to include navigation bars or banners in HTML documents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] This option can be used repeatedly to include multiple files.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note that if the output format is `odt`, this file must be in OpenDocument XML format suitable for insertion into the body of the document, and if the output is `docx`, this file must be in appropriate OpenXML format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Include contents of *FILE*, verbatim, at the end of the document body (before the `</body>` tag in HTML, or the `\end{document}` command in LaTeX).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] List of paths to search for images and other resources.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] The paths should be separated by `:` on Linux, UNIX, and macOS systems, and by `;` on Windows.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If `--resource-path` is not specified, the default resource path is the working directory.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note that, if `--resource-path` is specified, the working directory must be explicitly listed or it will not be searched.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] For example: `--resource-path=.:test` will search the working directory and the `test` subdirectory, in that order.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Search path components that come later on the command line will be searched before those that come earlier, so `--resource-path foo:bar --resource-path baz:bim` is equivalent to `--resource-path baz:bim:foo:bar`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Note that this option only has an effect when pandoc itself needs to find an image (e.g., in producing a PDF or docx, or when `--embed-resources` is used.) It will not cause image paths to be rewritten in other cases (e.g., when pandoc is generating LaTeX or HTML).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Set the request header *NAME* to the value *VAL* when making HTTP requests (for example, when a URL is given on the command line, or when resources used in a document must be downloaded).
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] If you’re behind a proxy, you also need to set the environment variable `http_proxy` to `http://...`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p01] Disable the certificate verification to allow access to unsecure HTTP resources (for example when the certificate is no longer valid or self signed).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Produce a standalone HTML file with no external dependencies, using `data:` URIs to incorporate the contents of linked scripts, stylesheets, images, and videos.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The resulting file should be “self-contained,” in the sense that it needs no external files and no net access to be displayed properly by a browser.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option works only with HTML output formats, including `html4`, `html5`, `html+lhs`, `html5+lhs`, `s5`, `slidy`, `slideous`, `dzslides`, and `revealjs`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Scripts, images, and stylesheets at absolute URLs will be downloaded; those at relative URLs will be sought relative to the working directory (if the first source file is local) or relative to the base URL (if the first source file is remote).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Elements with the attribute `data-external="1"` will be left alone; the documents they link to will not be incorporated in the document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Limitation: resources that are loaded dynamically through JavaScript cannot be incorporated; as a result, fonts may be missing when `--mathjax` is used, and some advanced features (e.g. zoom or speaker notes) may not work in an offline “self-contained” `reveal.js` slide show.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For SVG images, `img` tags with `data:` URIs are used, unless the image has the class `inline-svg`, in which case an inline SVG element is inserted.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This approach is recommended when there are many occurrences of the same SVG in a document, as `<use>` elements will be used to reduce duplication.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Include links to images instead of embedding the images in ODT.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use reference-style links, rather than inline links, in writing Markdown or reStructuredText.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The placement of link references is affected by the `--reference-location` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify whether footnotes (and references, if `reference-links` is set) are placed at the end of the current (top-level) block, the current section, or the document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Currently this option only affects the `markdown`, `muse`, `html`, `epub`, `slidy`, `s5`, `slideous`, `dzslides`, and `revealjs` writers.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] In slide formats, specifying `--reference-location=section` will cause notes to be rendered at the bottom of a slide.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify whether figure captions go above or below figures (default is `below`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option only affects HTML, LaTeX, Docx, ODT, and Typst output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify whether table captions go above or below tables (default is `above`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify whether to use ATX-style (`#`-prefixed) or Setext-style (underlined) headings for level 1 and 2 headings in Markdown output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] (The default is `atx`.) ATX-style headings are always used for levels 3+.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option also affects Markdown cells in `ipynb` output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Render tables as list tables in RST output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Treat top-level headings as the given division type in LaTeX, ConTeXt, DocBook, and TEI output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The hierarchy order is part, chapter, then section; all headings are shifted such that the top-level heading becomes the specified type.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The default behavior is to determine the best division type via heuristics: unless other conditions apply, `section` is chosen.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] When the `documentclass` variable is set to `report`, `book`, or `memoir` (unless the `article` option is specified), `chapter` is implied as the setting for this option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If `beamer` is the output format, specifying either `chapter` or `part` will cause top-level headings to become `\part{..}`, while second-level headings remain as their default type.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] In Docx output, this option adds section breaks before first-level headings if `chapter` is selected, and before first- and second-level headings if `part` is selected.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Footnote numbers will restart with each section break unless the reference doc modifies this.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Number section headings in LaTeX, ConTeXt, HTML, Docx, ms, or EPUB output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Sections with class `unnumbered` will never be numbered, even if `--number-sections` is specified.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The first number is added to the section number for level-1 headings, the second for level-2 headings, and so on.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] So, for example, if you want the first level-1 heading in your document to be numbered “6” instead of “1”, specify `--number-offset=5`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If your document starts with a level-2 heading which you want to be numbered “1.5”, specify `--number-offset=1,4`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `--number-offset` only directly affects the number of the first section heading in a document; subsequent numbers increment in the normal way.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Currently this feature only affects HTML and Docx output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use the `listings` package for LaTeX code blocks.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The package does not support multi-byte encoding for source code.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] To handle UTF-8 you would need to use a custom template.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This issue is fully documented here: Encoding issue with the listings package.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Make list items in slide shows display incrementally (one by one).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The default is for lists to be displayed all at once.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specifies that headings with the specified level create slides (for `beamer`, `revealjs`, `pptx`, `s5`, `slidy`, `slideous`, `dzslides`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Headings above this level in the hierarchy are used to divide the slide show into sections; headings below this level create subheads within a slide.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If a slide level of 0 is specified, slides will not be split automatically on headings, and horizontal rules must be used to indicate slide boundaries.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If a slide level is not specified explicitly, the slide level will be set automatically based on the contents of the document; see Structuring the slide show.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Wrap sections in `<section>` tags (or `<div>` tags for `html4`), and attach identifiers to the enclosing `<section>` (or `<div>`) rather than the heading itself (see Heading identifiers, below).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option only affects HTML output (and does not affect HTML slide formats).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify a method for obfuscating `mailto:` links in HTML documents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `none` leaves `mailto:` links as they are.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `javascript` obfuscates them using JavaScript.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `references` obfuscates them by printing their letters as decimal or hexadecimal character references.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify a prefix to be added to all identifiers and internal links in HTML and DocBook output, and to footnote numbers in Markdown and Haddock output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This is useful for preventing duplicate identifiers when generating fragments to be included in other pages.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify *STRING* as a prefix at the beginning of the title that appears in the HTML header (but not in the title as it appears at the beginning of the HTML body).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option only affects HTML (including HTML slide shows) and EPUB output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] It should be used together with `-s/--standalone`, because the link to the stylesheet goes in the document header.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] A stylesheet is required for generating EPUB.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If none is provided using this option (or the `css` or `stylesheet` metadata fields), pandoc will look for a file `epub.css` in the user data directory (see `--data-dir`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If it is not found there, sensible defaults will be used.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use the specified file as a style reference in producing a docx or ODT file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For best results, the reference docx should be a modified version of a docx file produced using pandoc.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The contents of the reference docx are ignored, but its stylesheets and document properties (including margins, page size, header, and footer) are used in the new docx.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If no reference docx is specified on the command line, pandoc will look for a file `reference.docx` in the user data directory (see `--data-dir`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If this is not found either, sensible defaults will be used.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] To produce a custom `reference.docx`, first get a copy of the default `reference.docx`: `pandoc -o custom-reference.docx --print-default-data-file reference.docx`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Then open `custom-reference.docx` in Word or LibreOffice, modify the styles as you wish, and save the file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For best results, the reference ODT should be a modified version of an ODT produced using pandoc.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The contents of the reference ODT are ignored, but its stylesheets are used in the new ODT.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If no reference ODT is specified on the command line, pandoc will look for a file `reference.odt` in the user data directory (see `--data-dir`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] To produce a custom `reference.odt`, first get a copy of the default `reference.odt`: `pandoc -o custom-reference.odt --print-default-data-file reference.odt`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Then open `custom-reference.odt` in LibreOffice, modify the styles as you wish, and save the file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Templates included with Microsoft PowerPoint 2013 (either with `.pptx` or `.potx` extension) are known to work, as are most templates derived from these.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For each name, the first layout found with that name will be used.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If no layout is found with one of the names, pandoc will output a warning and use the layout with that name from the default reference doc instead.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] All templates included with a recent version of MS PowerPoint will fit these criteria.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] You can also modify the default `reference.pptx`: first run `pandoc -o custom-reference.pptx --print-default-data-file reference.pptx`, and then modify `custom-reference.pptx` in MS PowerPoint (pandoc will use the layouts with the names listed above).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify the heading level at which to split an EPUB or chunked HTML document into separate files.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The default is to split into chapters at level-1 headings.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] In the case of EPUB, this option only affects the internal composition of the EPUB, not the way chapters and sections are displayed to users.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Some readers may be slow if the chapter files are too large, so for large documents with few level-1 headings, one might want to use a chapter level of 2 or 3.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify a template for the filenames in a `chunkedhtml` document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] In the template, `%n` will be replaced by the chunk number (padded with leading 0s to 3 digits), `%s` with the section number of the chunk, `%h` with the heading text (with formatting removed), `%i` with the section identifier.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For example, `section-%s-%i.html` might be resolved to `section-1.1-introduction.html`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The characters `/` and `\` are not allowed in chunk templates and will be ignored.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use the specified image as the EPUB cover.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] It is recommended that the image be less than 1000px in width and height.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Note that in a Markdown source document you can also specify `cover-image` in a YAML metadata block (see EPUB Metadata, below).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Determines whether a the title page is included in the EPUB (default is `true`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Look in the specified XML file for metadata for the EPUB.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The file should contain a series of Dublin Core elements.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Any of these may be overridden by elements in the metadata file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Note: if the source document is Markdown, a YAML metadata block in the document can be used instead.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option can be repeated to embed multiple fonts.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Wildcards can also be used: for example, `DejaVuSans-*.ttf`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] However, if you use wildcards on the command line, be sure to escape them or put the whole filename in single quotes, to prevent them from being interpreted by the shell.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Specify the subdirectory in the OCF container that is to hold the EPUB-specific contents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] To put the EPUB contents in the top level, use an empty string.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Determines how ipynb output cells are treated.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `all` means that all of the data formats included in the original are preserved.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `none` means that the contents of data cells are omitted.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `best` causes pandoc to try to pick the richest data block in each output cell that is compatible with the output format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use the specified engine when producing PDF output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Valid values are `pdflatex`, `lualatex`, `xelatex`, `latexmk`, `tectonic`, `wkhtmltopdf`, `weasyprint`, `pagedjs-cli`, `prince`, `context`, `groff`, `pdfroff`, and `typst`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If the engine is not in your PATH, the full path of the engine may be specified here.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option is normally intended to be used when a PDF file is specified as `-o/--output`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] However, it may still have an effect when other output formats are requested.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For example, `ms` output will include `.pdfhref` macros only if a `--pdf-engine` is selected, and the macros will be differently encoded depending on whether `groff` or `pdfroff` is specified.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use the given string as a command-line argument to the `pdf-engine`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For example, to use a persistent directory `foo` for `latexmk`’s auxiliary files, use `--pdf-engine-opt=-outdir=foo`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Note that no check for duplicate options is done.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Process the citations in the file, replacing them with rendered citations and adding a bibliography.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The style is controlled by a CSL stylesheet specified using the `--csl` option or the `csl` field in metadata.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] (If no stylesheet is specified, the `chicago-author-date` style will be used by default.) The citation processing transformation may be applied before or after filters or Lua filters (see `--filter`, `--lua-filter`): these transformations are applied in the order they appear on the command line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For more information, see the section on Citations.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Note: if this option is specified, the `citations` extension will be disabled automatically in the writer, to ensure that the citeproc-generated citations will be rendered instead of the format’s own citation syntax.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Set the `bibliography` field in the document’s metadata to *FILE*, overriding any value set in the metadata.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If you supply this argument multiple times, each *FILE* will be added to bibliography.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If *FILE* is a URL, it will be fetched via HTTP.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If *FILE* is not found relative to the working directory, it will be sought in the resource path (see `--resource-path`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Set the `csl` field in the document’s metadata to *FILE*, overriding any value set in the metadata.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] (This is equivalent to `--metadata csl=FILE`.) If *FILE* is a URL, it will be fetched via HTTP.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If *FILE* is not found relative to the working directory, it will be sought in the resource path (see `--resource-path`) and finally in the `csl` subdirectory of the pandoc user data directory.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Set the `citation-abbreviations` field in the document’s metadata to *FILE*, overriding any value set in the metadata.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] (This is equivalent to `--metadata citation-abbreviations=FILE`.) If *FILE* is a URL, it will be fetched via HTTP.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use `natbib` for citations in LaTeX output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option is not for use with the `--citeproc` option or with PDF output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] It is intended for use in producing a LaTeX file that can be processed with `bibtex`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use `biblatex` for citations in LaTeX output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] It is intended for use in producing a LaTeX file that can be processed with `bibtex` or `biber`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The default is to render TeX math as far as possible using Unicode characters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Formulas are put inside a `span` with `class="math"`, so that they may be styled differently from the surrounding text if needed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] However, this gives acceptable results only for basic math, usually you will want to use `--mathjax` or another of the following options.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use MathJax to display embedded TeX math in HTML output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] TeX math will be put between `\(...\)` (for inline math) or `\[...\]` (for display math) and wrapped in `<span>` tags with class `math`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Then the MathJax JavaScript will render it.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The *URL* should point to the `MathJax.js` load script.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If a *URL* is not provided, a link to the Cloudflare CDN will be inserted.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Convert TeX math to MathML (in `epub3`, `docbook4`, `docbook5`, `jats`, `html4` and `html5`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] MathML is supported natively by the main web browsers and select e-book readers.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Convert TeX formulas to `<img>` tags that link to an external script that converts formulas to images.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The formula will be URL-encoded and concatenated with the URL provided.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For SVG images you can for example use `--webtex https://latex.codecogs.com/svg.latex?`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If no URL is specified, the CodeCogs URL generating PNGs will be used (`https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Note: the `--webtex` option will affect Markdown output as well as HTML, which is useful if you’re targeting a version of Markdown without native math support.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use KaTeX to display embedded TeX math in HTML output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The *URL* is the base URL for the KaTeX library.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] That directory should contain a `katex.min.js` and a `katex.min.css` file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If a *URL* is not provided, a link to the KaTeX CDN will be inserted.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Enclose TeX math in `<eq>` tags in HTML output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The resulting HTML can then be processed by GladTeX to produce SVG images of the typeset formulas and an HTML file with these images embedded.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Print information about command-line arguments to *stdout*, then exit.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This option is intended primarily for use in wrapper scripts.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The first line of output contains the name of the output file specified with the `-o` option, or `-` (for *stdout*) if no output file was specified.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The remaining lines contain the command-line arguments, one per line, in the order they appear.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] These do not include regular pandoc options and their arguments, but do include any options appearing after a `--` separator at the end of the line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Ignore command-line arguments (for use in wrapper scripts).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If pandoc completes successfully, it will return exit code 0.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The `--defaults` option may be used to specify a package of options, in the form of a YAML or JSON file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Examples in this section will be given in YAML, but the equivalent forms in JSON will also work.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Fields that are omitted will just have their regular default values.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `${USERDATA}` may also be used; this will always resolve to the user data directory that is current when the defaults file is parsed, regardless of the setting of the environment variable `USERDATA`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `${.}` will resolve to the directory containing the defaults file itself.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] This environment variable interpolation syntax *only* works in fields that expect file paths.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Defaults files can be placed in the `defaults` subdirectory of the user data directory and used from any directory.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] For example, one could create a file specifying defaults for writing letters, save it as `letter.yaml` in the `defaults` subdirectory of the user data directory, and then invoke these defaults from any directory using `pandoc --defaults letter` or `pandoc -dletter`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] When multiple defaults are used, their contents will be combined.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The following tables show the mapping between the command line and defaults file entries.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The value of `input-files` may be left empty to indicate input from stdin, and it can be an empty sequence `[]` for no input.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Options specified in a defaults file itself always have priority over those in another file included with a `defaults:` entry.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `verbosity` can have the values `ERROR`, `WARNING`, or `INFO`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Metadata values specified in a defaults file are parsed as literal string text, not Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Filters will be assumed to be Lua filters if they have the `.lua` extension, and JSON filters otherwise.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] But the filter type can also be specified explicitly, as shown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] To include the built-in citeproc filter, use either `citeproc` or `{type: citeproc}`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] `cite-method` can be `citeproc`, `natbib`, or `biblatex`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If you want to use citeproc to format citations, you should also set ‘citeproc: true’.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If you need control over when the citeproc processing is done relative to other filters, you should instead use `citeproc` in the list of `filters` (see Reader options).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] In addition to the values listed above, `method` can have the value `plain`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If the command line option accepts a URL argument, an `url:` field can be added to `html-math-method:`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] When the `-s/--standalone` option is used, pandoc uses a template to add header and footer material that is needed for a self-standing document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] where *FORMAT* is the name of the output format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] A custom template can be specified using the `--template` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] You can also override the system default templates for a given output format *FORMAT* by putting a file `templates/default.*FORMAT*` in the user data directory (see `--data-dir`, above).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Note that `docx`, `odt`, and `pptx` output can also be customized using `--reference-doc`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Use a reference doc to adjust the styles in your document; use a template to handle variable interpolation and customize the presentation of metadata, the position of the table of contents, boilerplate text, etc.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Templates contain *variables*, which allow for the inclusion of arbitrary information at any point in the file.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] They may be set at the command line using the `-V/--variable` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If a variable is not set, pandoc will look for the key in the document’s metadata, which can be set using either YAML metadata blocks or with the `-M/--metadata` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] In addition, some variables are given default values by pandoc.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] See Variables below for a list of variables used in pandoc’s default templates.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If you use custom templates, you may need to revise them as pandoc changes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] We recommend tracking the changes in the default templates, and modifying your custom templates accordingly.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] An easy way to do this is to fork the pandoc-templates repository and merge in changes after each pandoc release.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] To mark variables and control structures in the template, either `$`…`$` or `${`…`}` may be used as delimiters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The styles may also be mixed in the same template, but the opening and closing delimiter must match in each case.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The opening delimiter may be followed by one or more spaces or tabs, which will be ignored.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The closing delimiter may be preceded by one or more spaces or tabs, which will be ignored.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] To include a literal `$` in the document, use `$$`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] A slot for an interpolated variable is a variable name surrounded by matched delimiters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Variable names must begin with a letter and can contain letters, numbers, `_`, `-`, and `.`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The keywords `it`, `if`, `else`, `endif`, `for`, `sep`, and `endfor` may not be used as variable names.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Variable names with periods are used to get at structured variable values.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] So, for example, `employee.salary` will return the value of the `salary` field of the object that is the value of the `employee` field.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] A conditional begins with `if(variable)` (enclosed in matched delimiters) and ends with `endif` (enclosed in matched delimiters).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] It may optionally contain an `else` (enclosed in matched delimiters).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The `if` section is used if `variable` has a true value, otherwise the `else` section is used (if present).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Note that in YAML metadata (and metadata specified on the command line using `-M/--metadata`), unquoted `true` and `false` will be interpreted as Boolean values.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] But a variable specified on the command line using `-V/--variable` will always be given a string value.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Hence a conditional `if(foo)` will be triggered if you use `-V foo=false`, but not if you use `-M foo=false`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] A for loop begins with `for(variable)` (enclosed in matched delimiters) and ends with `endfor` (enclosed in matched delimiters).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] You may optionally specify a separator between consecutive values using `sep` (enclosed in matched delimiters).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The material between `sep` and the `endfor` is the separator.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Instead of using `variable` inside the loop, the special anaphoric keyword `it` may be used.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Partials will be sought in the directory containing the main template.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The file name will be assumed to have the same extension as the main template if it lacks an extension.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If `articles` is an array, this will iterate over its values, applying the partial `bibentry()` to each one.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Note that the anaphoric keyword `it` must be used when iterating over partials.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] In the above examples, the `bibentry` partial should contain `it.title` (and so on) instead of `articles.title`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Final newlines are omitted from included partials.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] The separator in this case is literal and (unlike with `sep` in an explicit `for` loop) cannot contain interpolated variables or other template directives.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] To nest multiple lines to the same level, align them with the `^` directive in the template.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] If a variable occurs by itself on a line, preceded by whitespace and not followed by further text or directives on the same line, and the variable’s value contains multiple lines, it will be nested automatically.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Normally, spaces in the template itself (as opposed to values of the interpolated variables) are not breakable, but they can be made breakable in part of the template by using the `~` keyword (ended with another `~`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] A pipe transforms the value of a variable or partial.
[src:pandoc/manual-p02] Pipes are specified using a slash (`/`) between the variable name (or partial) and the pipe name.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] ) can be used to override the base direction in some output formats.
