[src:pandoc/manual-p03] title of table of contents (works only with EPUB, HTML, revealjs, opendocument, odt, docx, pptx, beamer, LaTeX).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] will be picked up from metadata, but cannot be set as a variable.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The behavior of some of the readers and writers can be adjusted by enabling or disabling various extensions.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] An extension can be enabled by adding `+EXTENSION` to the format name and disabled by adding `-EXTENSION`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] For example, `--from markdown_strict+footnotes` is strict Markdown with footnotes enabled, while `--from markdown-footnotes-pipe_tables` is pandoc’s Markdown without footnotes or pipe tables.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The Markdown reader and writer make by far the most use of extensions.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Extensions only used by them are therefore covered in the section Pandoc’s Markdown below (see Markdown variants for `commonmark` and `gfm`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] In the following, extensions that also work for other formats are covered.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Note that Markdown extensions added to the `ipynb` format affect Markdown cells in Jupyter notebooks (as do command-line options like `--markdown-headings`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Interpret straight quotes as curly quotes, `---` as em-dashes, `--` as en-dashes, and `...` as ellipses.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Note: If you are *writing* Markdown, then the `smart` extension has the reverse effect: what would have been curly quotes comes out straight.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] In LaTeX, `smart` means to use the standard TeX ligatures for quotation marks (`` and `''` for double quotes, ` and `'` for single quotes) and dashes (`--` for en-dash and `---` for em-dash).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If `smart` is disabled, then in reading LaTeX pandoc will parse these characters literally.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] In writing LaTeX, enabling `smart` tells pandoc to use the ligatures when possible; if `smart` is disabled pandoc will use unicode quotation mark and dash characters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] A heading without an explicitly specified identifier will be automatically assigned a unique identifier based on the heading text.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] These rules should, in most cases, allow one to determine the identifier from the heading text.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The exception is when several headings have the same text; in this case, the first will get an identifier as described above; the second will get the same identifier with `-1` appended; the third with `-2`; and so on.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] These identifiers are used to provide link targets in the table of contents generated by the `--toc|--table-of-contents` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] They also make it easy to provide links from one section of a document to another.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Note, however, that this method of providing links to sections works only in HTML, LaTeX, and ConTeXt formats.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If the `--section-divs` option is specified, then each section will be wrapped in a `section` (or a `div`, if `html4` was specified), and the identifier will be attached to the enclosing `<section>` (or `<div>`) tag rather than the heading itself.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This allows entire sections to be manipulated using JavaScript or treated differently in CSS.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Causes the identifiers produced by `auto_identifiers` to be pure ASCII.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Accents are stripped off of accented Latin letters, and non-Latin letters are omitted.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Changes the algorithm used by `auto_identifiers` to conform to GitHub’s method.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Spaces are converted to dashes (`-`), uppercase characters to lowercase characters, and punctuation characters other than `-` and `_` are removed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The extensions `tex_math_dollars`, `tex_math_gfm`, `tex_math_single_backslash`, and `tex_math_double_backslash` are described in the section about Pandoc’s Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] However, they can also be used with HTML input.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This is handy for reading web pages formatted using MathJax, for example.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Treat the document as literate Haskell source.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If you append `+lhs` (or `+literate_haskell`) to one of the formats above, pandoc will treat the document as literate Haskell source.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] reads literate Haskell source formatted with Markdown conventions and writes ordinary HTML (without bird tracks).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] writes HTML with the Haskell code in bird tracks, so it can be copied and pasted as literate Haskell source.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Note that GHC expects the bird tracks in the first column, so indented literate code blocks (e.g. inside an itemized environment) will not be picked up by the Haskell compiler.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] By default empty paragraphs are omitted.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Enables native numbering of figures and tables.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Links to headings, figures and tables inside the document are substituted with cross-references that will use the name or caption of the referenced item.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The original link text is replaced once the generated document is refreshed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This extension can be combined with `xrefs_number` in which case numbers will appear before the name.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Text in cross-references is only made consistent with the referenced item once the document has been refreshed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Links to headings, figures and tables inside the document are substituted with cross-references that will use the number of the referenced item.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This extension can be combined with `xrefs_name` in which case the name or caption numbers will appear after the number.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] For the `xrefs_number` to be useful heading numbers must be enabled in the generated document, also table and figure captions must be enabled using for example the `native_numbering` extension.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Numbers in cross-references are only visible in the final document once it has been refreshed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] When converting from docx, add `custom-styles` attributes for all docx styles, regardless of whether pandoc understands the meanings of these styles.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Because attributes cannot be added directly to paragraphs or text in the pandoc AST, paragraph styles will cause Divs to be created and character styles will cause Spans to be created to hold the attributes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] (Table styles will be added to the Table elements directly.) This extension can be used with docx custom styles.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] In the `muse` input format, this enables Text::Amuse extensions to Emacs Muse markup.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] In the `ipynb` input format, this causes Markdown cells to be included as raw Markdown blocks (allowing lossless round-tripping) rather than being parsed.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Use this only when you are targeting `ipynb` or a Markdown-based output format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] When the `citations` extension is enabled in `typst` (as it is by default), `typst` citations will be parsed as native pandoc citations, and native pandoc citations will be rendered as `typst` citations.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] When the `citations` extension is enabled in `org`, org-cite and org-ref style citations will be parsed as native pandoc citations, and org-cite citations will be used to render native pandoc citations.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] When `citations` is enabled in `docx`, citations inserted by Zotero or Mendeley or EndNote plugins will be parsed as native pandoc citations.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Some aspects of Pandoc’s Markdown fancy lists are also accepted in `org` input, mimicking the option `org-list-allow-alphabetical` in Emacs.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] As in Org Mode, enabling this extension allows lowercase and uppercase alphabetical markers for ordered lists to be parsed in addition to arabic ones.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Note that for Org, this does not include roman numerals or the `#` placeholder that are enabled by the extension in Pandoc’s Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] In the `jats` output formats, this causes reference items to be replaced with `<element-citation>` elements.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] These elements are not influenced by CSL styles, but all information on the item is included in tags.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] In the `context` output format this enables the use of Natural Tables (TABLE) instead of the default Extreme Tables (xtables).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Natural tables allow more fine-grained global customization but come at a performance penalty compared to extreme tables.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Interpret straight quotes as curly quotes during parsing.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] When *writing* Org, then the `smart_quotes` extension has the reverse effect: what would have been curly quotes comes out straight.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This extension is implied if `smart` is enabled.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Interpret `---` as em-dashes, `--` as en-dashes, `\-` as shy hyphen, and `...` as ellipses.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Enabling this extension with `context` output will produce markup suitable for the production of tagged PDFs.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This includes additional markers for paragraphs and alternative markup for emphasized text.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The `emphasis-command` template variable is set if the extension is enabled.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Pandoc understands an extended and slightly revised version of John Gruber’s Markdown syntax.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This document explains the syntax, noting differences from original Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Except where noted, these differences can be suppressed by using the `markdown_strict` format instead of `markdown`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Extensions can be enabled or disabled to specify the behavior more granularly.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] See also Extensions above, for extensions that work also on other formats.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This principle has guided pandoc’s decisions in finding syntax for tables, footnotes, and other extensions.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] There is, however, one respect in which pandoc’s aims are different from the original aims of Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Whereas Markdown was originally designed with HTML generation in mind, pandoc is designed for multiple output formats.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Thus, while pandoc allows the embedding of raw HTML, it discourages it, and provides other, non-HTMLish ways of representing important document elements like definition lists, tables, mathematics, and footnotes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] A paragraph is one or more lines of text followed by one or more blank lines.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Newlines are treated as spaces, so you can reflow your paragraphs as you like.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If you need a hard line break, put two or more spaces at the end of a line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] A backslash followed by a newline is also a hard line break.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Note: in multiline and grid table cells, this is the only way to create a hard line break, since trailing spaces in the cells are ignored.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] There are two kinds of headings: Setext and ATX.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The heading text can contain inline formatting, such as emphasis (see Inline formatting, below).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] An ATX-style heading consists of one to six `#` signs and a line of text, optionally followed by any number of `#` signs.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Original Markdown syntax does not require a blank line before a heading.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Pandoc does require this (except, of course, at the beginning of the document).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The reason for the requirement is that it is all too easy for a `#` to end up at the beginning of a line by accident (perhaps through line wrapping).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Many Markdown implementations do not require a space between the opening `#`s of an ATX heading and the heading text, so that `#5 bolt` and `#hashtag` count as headings.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] With this extension, pandoc does require the space.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] See also the `auto_identifiers` extension above.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Note that although this syntax allows assignment of classes and key/value attributes, writers generally don’t use all of this information.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Identifiers, classes, and key/value attributes are used in HTML and HTML-based formats such as EPUB and slidy.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Identifiers are used for labels and link anchors in the LaTeX, ConTeXt, Textile, Jira markup, and AsciiDoc writers.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Headings with the class `unnumbered` will not be numbered, even if `--number-sections` is specified.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] A single hyphen (`-`) in an attribute context is equivalent to `.unnumbered`, and preferable in non-English documents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If the `unlisted` class is present in addition to `unnumbered`, the heading will not be included in a table of contents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Pandoc behaves as if reference links have been defined for each heading.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If there are multiple headings with identical text, the corresponding reference will link to the first one only, and you will need to use explicit links to link to the others, as described above.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Like regular reference links, these references are case-insensitive.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Explicit link reference definitions always take priority over implicit heading references.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Markdown uses email conventions for quoting blocks of text.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] A block quotation is one or more paragraphs or other block elements (such as lists or headings), with each line preceded by a `>` character and an optional space.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Among the block elements that can be contained in a block quote are other block quotes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If the `>` character is followed by an optional space, that space will be considered part of the block quote marker and not part of the indentation of the contents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Original Markdown syntax does not require a blank line before a block quote.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The reason for the requirement is that it is all too easy for a `>` to end up at the beginning of a line by accident (perhaps through line wrapping).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] A block of text indented four spaces (or one tab) is treated as verbatim text: that is, special characters do not trigger special formatting, and all spaces and line breaks are preserved.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The initial (four space or one tab) indentation is not considered part of the verbatim text, and is removed in the output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Note: blank lines in the verbatim text need not begin with four spaces.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] In addition to standard indented code blocks, pandoc supports *fenced* code blocks.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] These begin with a row of three or more tildes (`~`) and end with a row of tildes that must be at least as long as the starting row.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Everything between these lines is treated as code.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Like regular code blocks, fenced code blocks must be separated from surrounding text by blank lines.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Same as `fenced_code_blocks`, but uses backticks (`) instead of tildes (`~`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Here `mycode` is an identifier, `haskell` and `numberLines` are classes, and `startFrom` is an attribute with value `100`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Some output formats can use this information to do syntax highlighting.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Currently, the only output formats that use this information are HTML, LaTeX, Docx, Ms, and PowerPoint.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If highlighting is supported for your output format and language, then the code block above will appear highlighted, with numbered lines.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The `numberLines` (or `number-lines`) class will cause the lines of the code block to be numbered, starting with `1` or the value of the `startFrom` attribute.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The `lineAnchors` (or `line-anchors`) class will cause the lines to be clickable anchors in HTML output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] If the `fenced_code_attributes` extension is disabled, but input contains class attribute(s) for the code block, the first class attribute will be printed after the opening fence as a bare word.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] To prevent all highlighting, use the `--syntax-highlighting=none` option.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] To set the highlighting style or method, use `--syntax-highlighting`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] For more information on highlighting, see Syntax highlighting, below.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] A line block is a sequence of lines beginning with a vertical bar (`|`) followed by a space.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The division into lines will be preserved in the output, as will any leading spaces; otherwise, the lines will be formatted as Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] The lines can be hard-wrapped if needed, but the continuation line must begin with a space.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Inline formatting (such as emphasis) is allowed in the content (though it can’t cross line boundaries).
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] Block-level formatting (such as block quotes or lists) is not recognized.
[src:pandoc/manual-p03] This syntax is borrowed from reStructuredText.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A bullet list is a list of bulleted list items.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A bulleted list item begins with a bullet (`*`, `+`, or `-`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The bullets need not be flush with the left margin; they may be indented one, two, or three spaces.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The bullet must be followed by whitespace.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A list item may contain multiple paragraphs and other block-level content.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] However, subsequent paragraphs must be preceded by a blank line and indented to line up with the first non-space content after the list marker.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In this case the preceding blank line is optional.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The nested list must be indented to line up with the first non-space character after the list marker of the containing list item.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] As noted above, Markdown allows you to write list items “lazily,” instead of indenting continuation lines.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] However, if there are multiple paragraphs or other blocks in a list item, the first line of each must be indented.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Ordered lists work just like bulleted lists, except that the items begin with enumerators rather than bullets.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In original Markdown, enumerators are decimal numbers followed by a period and a space.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Unlike original Markdown, pandoc allows ordered list items to be marked with uppercase and lowercase letters and roman numerals, in addition to Arabic numerals.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] List markers may be enclosed in parentheses or followed by a single right-parenthesis or period.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Note: the ‘`#`’ ordered list marker doesn’t work with `commonmark`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Pandoc also pays attention to the type of list marker used, and to the starting number, and both of these are preserved where possible in the output format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Pandoc will start a new list each time a different type of list marker is used.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Pandoc supports task lists, using the syntax of GitHub-Flavored Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Each term must fit on one line, which may optionally be followed by a blank line, and must be followed by one or more definitions.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A definition begins with a colon or tilde, which may be indented one or two spaces.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A term may have multiple definitions, and each definition may consist of one or more indented block elements (paragraph, code block, list, etc.).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The blocks in the definition shoud be indented to the column of the first non-space content after the `:` or `~` marker, or (if the `four_space_rule` extension is enabled) four spaces or one tab stop.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] If you leave space before the definition (as in the example above), the text of the definition will be treated as a paragraph.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In some output formats, this will mean greater spacing between term/definition pairs.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Note that space between items in a definition list is required.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The special list marker `@` can be used for sequentially numbered examples.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The first list item with a `@` marker will be numbered ‘1’, the next ‘2’, and so on, throughout the document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The numbered examples need not occur in a single list; each new list using `@` will take up where the last stopped.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The label can be any string of alphanumeric characters, underscores, or hyphens.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Continuation paragraphs in example lists must always be indented four spaces, regardless of the length of the list marker.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] That is, example lists always behave as if the `four_space_rule` extension is set.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This is because example labels tend to be long, and indenting content to the first non-space character after the label would be awkward.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This only works reliably, though, if the repeated item is in a list by itself, because each numbered example list will be numbered continuously from its starting number.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] What if you want to put an indented code block after a list?
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Here pandoc (like other Markdown implementations) will treat `{ my code block }` as the second paragraph of item two, and not as a code block.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] We strongly recommend that horizontal rules be separated from surrounding text by blank lines.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] If a horizontal rule is not followed by a blank line, pandoc may try to interpret the lines that follow as a YAML metadata block or a table.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The first three kinds presuppose the use of a fixed-width font, such as Courier.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The fourth kind can be used with proportionally spaced fonts, as it does not require lining up columns.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A caption may optionally be provided with all 4 kinds of tables (as illustrated in the examples below).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A caption is a paragraph beginning with the string `Table:` (or `table:` or just `:`), which will be stripped off.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] It may appear either before or after the table.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The header and table rows must each fit on one line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The table must end with a blank line, or a line of dashes followed by a blank line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The column header row may be omitted, provided a dashed line is used to end the table.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] When the header row is omitted, column alignments are determined on the basis of the first line of the table body.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] So, in the tables above, the columns would be right, left, center, and right aligned, respectively.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Multiline tables allow header and table rows to span multiple lines of text (but cells that span multiple columns or rows of the table are not supported).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In multiline tables, the table parser pays attention to the widths of the columns, and the writers try to reproduce these relative widths in the output.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] So, if you find that one of the columns is too narrow in the output, try widening it in the Markdown source.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] It is possible for a multiline table to have just one row, but the row should be followed by a blank line (and then the row of dashes that ends the table), or the table may be interpreted as a simple table.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The row of `=`s separates the header from the table body, and can be omitted for a headerless table.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The cells of grid tables may contain arbitrary block elements (multiple paragraphs, code blocks, lists, etc.).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The foot must always be placed at the very bottom of the table.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Grid tables can be created easily using Emacs’ table-mode (`M-x table-insert`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The syntax is identical to PHP Markdown Extra tables.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The beginning and ending pipe characters are optional, but pipes are required between all columns.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The colons indicate column alignment as shown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] To simulate a headerless table, include a header with blank cells.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Since the pipes indicate column boundaries, columns need not be vertically aligned, as they are in the above example.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The cells of pipe tables cannot contain block elements like paragraphs and lists, and cannot span multiple lines.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] If any line of the Markdown source is longer than the column width (see `--columns`), then the table will take up the full text width and the cell contents will wrap, with the relative cell widths determined by the number of dashes in the line separating the table header from the table body.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] (For example `---|-` would make the first column 3/4 and the second column 1/4 of the full text width.) On the other hand, if no lines are wider than column width, then cell contents will not be wrapped, and the cells will be sized to their contents.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The difference is that `+` is used instead of `|`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Other orgtbl features are not supported.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In particular, to get non-default column alignment, you’ll need to add colons as above.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Attributes may be attached to tables by including them at the end of the caption.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Except inside a code block or inline code, any punctuation or space character preceded by a backslash will be treated literally, even if it would normally indicate formatting.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A backslash-escaped space is parsed as a nonbreaking space.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In HTML and XML output, it will appear as a literal unicode nonbreaking space character (note that it will thus actually look “invisible” in the generated HTML source; you can still use the `--ascii` command-line option to make it appear as an explicit entity).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A backslash-escaped newline (i.e. a backslash occurring at the end of a line) is parsed as a hard line break.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] It will appear in TeX output as `\\` and in HTML as `<br />`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This is a nice alternative to Markdown’s “invisible” way of indicating hard line breaks using two trailing spaces on a line.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Backslash escapes do not work in verbatim contexts.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Because `_` is sometimes used inside words and identifiers, pandoc does not interpret a `_` surrounded by alphanumeric characters as an emphasis marker.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] To strike out a section of text with a horizontal line, begin and end it with `~~`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Superscripts may be written by surrounding the superscripted text by `^` characters; subscripts may be written by surrounding the subscripted text by `~` characters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The text between `^...^` or `~...~` may not contain spaces or newlines.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] If the superscripted or subscripted text contains spaces, these spaces must be escaped with backslashes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] (This is to prevent accidental superscripting and subscripting through the ordinary use of `~` and `^`, and also bad interactions with footnotes.) Thus, if you want the letter P with ‘a cat’ in subscripts, use `P~a\ cat~`, not `P~a cat~`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The general rule is that a verbatim span starts with a string of consecutive backticks (optionally followed by a space) and ends with a string of the same number of backticks (optionally preceded by a space).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This will work in all output formats that support underline.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This will work in all output formats that support small caps.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This will work in all output formats that support highlighting.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Anything between two `$` characters will be treated as TeX math.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The opening `$` must have a non-space character immediately to its right, while the closing `$` must have a non-space character immediately to its left, and must not be followed immediately by a digit.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] If for some reason you need to enclose text in literal `$` characters, backslash-escape them and they won’t be treated as math delimiters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] (In this case, the delimiters may be separated from the formula by whitespace.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] TeX math will be printed in all output formats.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] the bracketed material will also include inline or display math delimiters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] It will be rendered, if possible, using Unicode characters, and will otherwise appear verbatim.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] It will be rendered, if possible, using MathML.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Otherwise it will be rendered, if possible, using Unicode characters.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] It will be rendered using OMML math markup.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] option is used, formulas are rendered as images using CodeCogs or other compatible web service, downloaded and embedded in the e-book.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The way math is rendered in HTML will depend on the command-line options selected.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Markdown allows you to insert raw HTML (or DocBook) anywhere in a document (except verbatim contexts, where `<`, `>`, and `&` are interpreted literally).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The raw HTML is passed through unchanged in HTML, S5, Slidy, Slideous, DZSlides, EPUB, Markdown, CommonMark, Emacs Org mode, and Textile output, and suppressed in other formats.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] For a more explicit way of including raw HTML in a Markdown document, see the `raw_attribute` extension.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In the CommonMark format, if `raw_html` is enabled, superscripts, subscripts, strikeouts and small capitals will be represented as HTML.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Otherwise, plain-text fallbacks will be used.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Note that even if `raw_html` is disabled, tables will be rendered with HTML syntax if they cannot use pipe syntax.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Original Markdown allows you to include HTML “blocks”: blocks of HTML between balanced tags that are separated from the surrounding text with blank lines, and start and end at the left margin.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Within these blocks, everything is interpreted as HTML, not Markdown; so (for example), `*` does not signify emphasis.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Pandoc behaves this way when the `markdown_strict` format is used; but by default, pandoc interprets material between HTML block tags as Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] whereas `Markdown.pl` will preserve it as is.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] There is one exception to this rule: text between `<script>`, `<style>`, `<pre>`, and `<textarea>` tags is not interpreted as Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This departure from original Markdown should make it easier to mix Markdown with HTML block elements.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] For example, one can surround a block of Markdown text with `<div>` tags without preventing it from being interpreted as Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Use native pandoc `Div` blocks for content inside `<div>` tags.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] For the most part this should give the same output as `markdown_in_html_blocks`, but it makes it easier to write pandoc filters to manipulate groups of blocks.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Use native pandoc `Span` blocks for content inside `<span>` tags.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] For the most part this should give the same output as `raw_html`, but it makes it easier to write pandoc filters to manipulate groups of inlines.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In addition to raw HTML, pandoc allows raw LaTeX, TeX, and ConTeXt to be included in a document.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Inline TeX commands will be preserved and passed unchanged to the LaTeX and ConTeXt writers.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] the material between the begin and end tags will be interpreted as raw LaTeX, not as Markdown.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] For a more explicit and flexible way of including raw TeX in a Markdown document, see the `raw_attribute` extension.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Inline LaTeX is ignored in output formats other than Markdown, LaTeX, Emacs Org mode, and ConTeXt.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Inline spans and fenced code blocks with a special kind of attribute will be parsed as raw content with the designated format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The format name should match the target format name (see `-t/--to`, above, for a list, or use `pandoc --list-output-formats`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Use `openxml` for `docx` output, `opendocument` for `odt` output, `html5` for `epub3` output, `html4` for `epub2` output, and `latex`, `beamer`, `ms`, or `html5` for `pdf` output (depending on what you use for `--pdf-engine`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This extension presupposes that the relevant kind of inline code or fenced code block is enabled.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Thus, for example, to use a raw attribute with a backtick code block, `backtick_code_blocks` must be enabled.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The raw attribute cannot be combined with regular attributes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] When this extension is enabled, pandoc will parse LaTeX macro definitions and apply the resulting macros to all LaTeX math and raw LaTeX.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Note that LaTeX macros will not be applied if they occur inside a raw span or block marked with the `raw_attribute` extension.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] When `latex_macros` is disabled, the raw LaTeX and math will not have macros applied.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] This is usually a better approach when you are targeting LaTeX or PDF.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Macro definitions in LaTeX will be passed through as raw LaTeX only if `latex_macros` is not enabled.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Macro definitions in Markdown source (or other formats allowing `raw_tex`) will be passed through regardless of whether `latex_macros` is enabled.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Markdown allows links to be specified in several ways.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] An inline link consists of the link text in square brackets, followed by the URL in parentheses.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] There can be no space between the bracketed part and the parenthesized part.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The link text can contain formatting (such as emphasis), but the title cannot.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] An *explicit* reference link has two parts, the link itself and the link definition, which may occur elsewhere in the document (either before or after the link).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The link consists of link text in square brackets, followed by a label in square brackets.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] (There cannot be space between the two unless the `spaced_reference_links` extension is enabled.) If the label is empty (`[]`), then it will be implicitly be taken to be the same as the link text; thus `[foo][]` is equivalent to `[foo][foo]`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The link definition consists of the bracketed label, followed by a colon and a space, followed by the URL, and optionally (after a space) a link title either in quotes or in parentheses.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The label must not be parseable as a citation (assuming the `citations` extension is enabled): citations take precedence over link labels.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Note that link labels are not case sensitive.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The link definition may come either before or after a reference link that uses the label.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Note: In some Markdown implementations, reference link definitions cannot occur in nested constructions such as list items or block quotes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Pandoc lifts this arbitrary-seeming restriction.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] To link to another section of the same document, use the automatically generated identifier (see Heading identifiers).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Internal links are currently supported for HTML formats (including HTML slide shows and EPUB), LaTeX, and ConTeXt.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A link immediately preceded by a `!` will be treated as an image.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] An image with nonempty alt text, occurring by itself in a paragraph, will be rendered as a figure with a caption.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The image’s description will be used as the caption.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] How this is rendered depends on the output format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] In those formats, you’ll just get an image in a paragraph by itself, with no caption.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] If you just want a regular inline image, just make sure it is not the only thing in the paragraph.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Note that in reveal.js slide shows, an image in a paragraph by itself that has the `r-stretch` class will fill the screen, and the caption and figure tags will be omitted.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] For LaTeX output, you can specify a figure’s positioning by adding the `latex-placement` attribute.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] For HTML and EPUB, all known HTML5 attributes except `width` and `height` (but including `srcset` and `sizes`) are passed through as is.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Unknown attributes are passed through as custom attributes, with `data-` prepended.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The other writers ignore attributes that are not specifically supported by their output format.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The `width` and `height` attributes on images are treated specially.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] When used without a unit, the unit is assumed to be pixels.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] However, any of the following unit identifiers can be used: `px`, `cm`, `mm`, `in`, `inch` and `%`.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] There must not be any spaces between the number and the unit.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Using the `native_divs` and `native_spans` extensions (see above), HTML syntax can be used as part of Markdown to create native `Div` and `Span` elements in the pandoc AST (as opposed to raw HTML).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Allow special fenced syntax for native `Div` blocks.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] A Div starts with a fence containing at least three consecutive colons plus some attributes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The attributes may optionally be followed by another string of consecutive colons.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Note: the `commonmark` parser doesn’t permit colons after the attributes.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The attribute syntax is exactly as in fenced code blocks (see Extension: `fenced_code_attributes`).
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] As with fenced code blocks, one can use either attributes in curly braces or a single unbraced word, which will be treated as a class name.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The Div ends with another line containing a string of at least three consecutive colons.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] The fenced Div should be separated by blank lines from preceding and following blocks.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Fences without attributes are always closing fences.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] Unlike with fenced code blocks, the number of colons in the closing fence need not match the number in the opening fence.
[src:pandoc/manual-p04] However, it can be helpful for visual clarity to use fences of different lengths to distinguish nested divs from their parents.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] A **markup language** is a text-encoding system which specifies the structure and formatting of a document and potentially the relationships among its parts.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Markup can control the display of a document or enrich its content to facilitate automated processing.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] A markup language is a set of rules governing what markup information may be included in a document and how it is combined with the content of the document in a way to facilitate use by humans and computer programs.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The idea and terminology evolved from the marking up of paper manuscripts (e.g., with revision instructions by editors), traditionally written with a red pen or blue pencil on authors' manuscripts.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Older markup languages, which typically focus on typesetting and presentation, include troff, TeX, and LaTeX.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Scribe and most modern markup languages, such as XML, identify document components (for example headings, paragraphs, and tables), with the expectation that technology, such as stylesheets, will be used to apply formatting or other processing.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Some markup languages, such as the widely used HTML, have pre-defined presentation semantics, meaning that their specifications prescribe some aspects of how to present the structured data on particular media.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] HTML, like DocBook, Open eBook, JATS, and many others, are based on the markup metalanguages XML and SGML.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] That is, SGML and XML allow designers to specify particular schemas, which determine which elements, attributes, and other features are permitted, and where.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] A key characteristic of most markup languages is that they allow combining markup with content such as text and pictures.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] For example, if a few words in a sentence need to be emphasized, or identified as a proper name, defined term, or another special item, the markup may be inserted between the characters of the sentence.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The word *markup* is derived from the traditional publishing practice of *marking up* a manuscript, which involves adding handwritten annotations in the form of conventional symbolic printer's instructions—in the margins and text of a paper or printed manuscript.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] For centuries, this task was done primarily by skilled typographers known as *markup men* or *markers* who marked up text to indicate what typeface, style, and size should be applied to each part, and then passed the manuscript to others for typesetting by hand or machine.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The markup was also commonly applied by editors, proofreaders, publishers, and graphic designers, and by authors themselves, all of whom might also mark things such as corrections and changes.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] There are three general categories of electronic markup, articulated by James Coombs, Allen Renear, and Steven DeRose in 1987, and Tim Bray in 2003.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Presentational markup is used by traditional word-processing systems.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Binary codes embedded within document text produce the WYSIWYG ('what you see is what you get') effect.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Such markup is usually hidden from human users, even authors and editors.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Such systems use procedural and descriptive markup internally but convert them to present the user with formatted arrangements of type.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Markup is embedded in text which provides instructions for programs to process the text.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Well-known examples include troff, TeX, and Markdown.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Generally, software processes the text sequentially from beginning to end, following the instructions as encountered.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Such text is often edited with the markup visible and directly manipulated by the author.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Popular procedural markup systems usually include programming constructs, especially macros, allowing complex sets of instructions to be invoked by a simple name (and perhaps a few parameters).
[src:pandoc/markup-language] This is much faster, less error-prone, and more maintenance-friendly than re-stating the same or similar instructions in many places.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Descriptive markup is specifically used to describe parts of the document for what they are, rather than how they should be processed.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Well-known systems that provide many such labels include LaTeX, HTML, and XML.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The objective is to decouple the structure of the document from any particular treatment or rendition of it.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Such markup is often described as *semantic*.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] An example of a descriptive markup is HTML's `<cite>` tag, which is used to label a citation.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Descriptive markup—sometimes called *logical markup* or *conceptual markup*—encourages authors to write in a way that describes the material conceptually, rather than visually.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] There is considerable overlap and concurrent use of markup types.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In modern word-processing systems, presentational markup is often saved in descriptive-markup-oriented systems such as XML, and then processed procedurally by implementations.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The programming in procedural-markup systems, such as TeX, may be used to create higher-level markup systems that are more descriptive in nature, such as LaTeX.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In recent years, several markup languages have been developed with ease of use as a key goal, and without input from standards organizations, aimed at allowing authors to create formatted text via web browsers, for example in wikis and web forums.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] These are sometimes called lightweight markup languages.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Markdown, BBCode, and the markup language used by Wikipedia are examples of such languages.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The first well-known public presentation of markup languages in computer text processing was made by William W.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Tunnicliffe at a conference in 1967, although he preferred to call it *generic coding.* It can be seen as a response to the emergence of processing programs such as RUNOFF that each used their own control notation, often specific to the target typesetting device.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In the 1970s, Tunnicliffe led the development of a standard called GenCode for the publishing industry.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Book designer Stanley Rice published speculation along similar lines in 1970.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Brian Reid, in his 1980 dissertation at Carnegie Mellon University, developed a theory and working implementation of descriptive markup in actual use.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] However, IBM researcher Charles Goldfarb is more commonly considered the inventor of markup languages.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Goldfarb developed the basic idea while working on a primitive document management system intended for law firms in 1969, and helped invent IBM's Generalized Markup Language (GML) later that same year.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] GML was first publicly disclosed in 1973.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In 1975, Goldfarb moved from Cambridge, Massachusetts to Silicon Valley and became a product planner at the IBM Almaden Research Center.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] There, he convinced IBM's executives to deploy GML commercially in 1978 as part of IBM's Document Composition Facility product, and it was widely used in business within a few years.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML), the first standard descriptive markup language, was based on both GML and GenCode.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] It was the result of an International Organization for Standardization (ISO) committee that was first chaired by Tunnicliffe, and which Goldfarb also worked on beginning in 1974.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Goldfarb eventually became chair of the committee.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] SGML was first released by ISO as the ISO 8879 standard in October 1986.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Some early examples of computer markup languages available outside the publishing industry can be found in typesetting tools on Unix systems such as troff and nroff.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In these systems, formatting commands were inserted into the document text so that typesetting software could format the text according to the editor's specifications.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] It was a trial and error iterative process to correctly print a document.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The availability of WYSIWYG publishing software supplanted much use of these languages among casual users, though professional publishing work still uses markup to specify the non-visual structure of texts, and WYSIWYG editors now usually save documents in a markup-language-based format.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Another major publishing standard is TeX, created and refined by Donald Knuth in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] TeX concentrated on the detailed layout of text and font descriptions to typeset mathematical books.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] This required Knuth to spend considerable time investigating the art of typesetting.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] TeX is mainly used in academia, where it is a *de facto* standard in many scientific disciplines.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] A TeX macro package known as LaTeX provides a descriptive markup system on top of TeX, and is widely used both among the scientific community and the publishing industry.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The first language to make a clear distinction between structure and presentation was Scribe, developed by Brian Reid and described in his doctoral thesis in 1980.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Scribe was revolutionary in a number of ways, introducing the idea of styles separated from the marked-up document, and a grammar that controlled the usage of descriptive elements.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Scribe influenced the development of GML and later SGML, and is a direct ancestor to HTML and LaTeX.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In the early 1980s, the idea that markup should focus on the structural aspects of a document and leave the visual presentation of that structure to the interpreter led to the creation of SGML.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The language was developed by a committee chaired by Goldfarb.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] It incorporated ideas from many different sources, including Tunnicliffe's project, GenCode.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Sharon Adler, Anders Berglund, and James A.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Marke were also key members of the SGML committee.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] SGML specifies a syntax for including the markup in documents, as well as one for separately describing what tags are allowed, and where (the document type definition (DTD), later known as a schema).
[src:pandoc/markup-language] This allows authors to create and use any markup they want, selecting tags that make the most sense to them and are named in their own natural languages, while also allowing automated verification.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Thus, SGML is properly a metalanguage, and many markup languages are derived from it.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] From the late 1980s onward, most substantial new markup languages have been based on SGML, including the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) guidelines and DocBook.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] SGML was promulgated as the ISO 8879 standard in 1986.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] SGML found wide acceptance and use in fields with very large-scale documentation requirements.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] However, many found it cumbersome and difficult to learn—a side effect of its design attempting to do too much and being too flexible.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] For example, SGML made end tags (or start tags, or both) optional in certain contexts, because its developers thought markup would be done manually by overworked support staff who would appreciate saving keystrokes.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In 1989, computer scientist Tim Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system, then specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by SGMLguid, an in-house SGML-based documentation format at CERN, and very similar to the sample schema in the SGML standard.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Berners-Lee considered HTML an SGML application.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formally defined it as such with the mid-1993 publication of the first proposal for an HTML specification: "Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)" by Berners-Lee and Dan Connolly, which included an SGML DTD to define the grammar.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] These formatting commands were derived from those used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Steven DeRose argues that HTML's use of descriptive markup (and the influence of SGML in particular) was a major factor in the success of the Web, because of the flexibility and extensibility that it enabled.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] HTML became the main markup language for creating web pages and other information that can be displayed in a web browser and is likely the most used markup language in the world in the 21st century.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] XML (Extensible Markup Language) is a widely used meta markup language.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] It was developed by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in a committee created and chaired by Jon Bosak.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The main purpose of XML was to simplify SGML by focusing on a particular use case—documents on the Internet.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] XML remains a metalanguage like SGML, allowing users to create any tags needed (hence *extensible*) and then describing those tags and their permitted uses.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] XML adoption was hastened by the fact that every XML document can be written so that it is also an SGML document, allowing existing SGML users and software to switch to XML fairly easily.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] At the same time, XML eliminates many complex features of SGML to simplify implementation environments such as documents and publications.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] It appears to balance simplicity and flexibility, as well as support very robust schema definitions and validation tools, and was rapidly adopted for many uses.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] XML is now widely used for communicating data between applications, serializing program data, for hardware communication protocols, vector graphics, and other uses besides documents.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] From January 2000 until HTML 5 was released, all W3C recommendations for HTML were based on XML, using XHTML (Extensible HyperText Markup Language).
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The language specification requires that XHTML documents be *well-formed* XML documents.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] This allows for more rigorous and robust documents, by avoiding many syntax errors which historically led to unwanted browser behavior, while still using document components familiar to HTML users.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Another difference is that all attribute values in tags must be quoted.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Both these differences are commonly criticized as verbose but also praised because they make it far easier to detect, localize, and repair errors.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Finally, all tag and attribute names within the XHTML namespace must be lowercase to be valid.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] HTML, on the other hand, was case-insensitive.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Many XML-based applications exist, including the Resource Description Framework as RDF/XML, XForms, DocBook, SOAP, and the Web Ontology Language (OWL).
[src:pandoc/markup-language] For a partial list of these, see list of XML markup languages.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] A common feature of many markup languages is that they intermix the text of a document with markup instructions in the same data stream or file.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] This is not necessary; it is possible to isolate markup from text content, using pointers, offsets, IDs, or other methods to coordinate the two.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Such *standoff* markup is typical for the internal representations that programs use to work with marked-up documents.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] However, *embedded* or *inline* markup is much more common elsewhere.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The codes enclosed in angle-brackets `<like this>` are markup instructions (known as *tags*), while the text between these instructions is the actual text of the document.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The codes `h1`, `p`, and `em` are examples of *semantic* markup, in that they describe the intended purpose or the meaning of the text they include.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Specifically, `h1` means the enclosed text is a *first-level heading*, `p` means a *paragraph*, and `em` means an *emphasized* word or phrase.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] A program interpreting such structural markup may apply its own rules or styles for presenting the various pieces of text, using different typefaces, boldness, font size, indentation, color, or other styles, as desired.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] For example, a tag such as `h1` might be presented in a large bold sans-serif typeface in an article, or it might be underscored in a monospaced (fixed-width font) document, or it might not change the presentation at all.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In contrast, the `i` tag in HTML 4 is an example of *presentational* markup, which is generally used to specify a characteristic of the text without specifying the reason for that appearance.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] In this case, the `i` element dictates the use of an italic typeface.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] However, in HTML 5, this element has been repurposed with a more semantic usage: to denote "a span of text in an alternate voice or mood, or otherwise offset from the normal prose in a manner indicating a different quality of text".
[src:pandoc/markup-language] For example, it is appropriate to use the `i` element to indicate a taxonomic designation or a phrase in another language.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The change was made to ease the transition from HTML 4 to 5 as smoothly as possible so that deprecated uses of presentational elements would preserve the most likely intended meaning.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] TEI has published extensive guidelines for how to encode texts of interest in the humanities and social sciences, developed through years of international cooperative work.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] These guidelines are used for encoding historical documents, and the works of particular scholars, periods, and genres.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] While the idea of markup language originated with text documents, they are increasingly used in the presentation of other types of information, including playlists, vector graphics, web services, content syndication, and user interfaces.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] Most of these are XML applications because XML is a well-defined and extensible language.
[src:pandoc/markup-language] The use of XML has also led to the possibility of combining multiple markup languages into a single profile, like XHTML+SMIL and XHTML+MathML+SVG.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] Pandoc dubs itself a "markup format" converter.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] It can take a document in one of the supported formats and convert only its markup to another format.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] Maintaining the look and feel of the document is not a priority.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] Plug-ins for custom formats can also be written in Lua, which has been used to create an exporting tool for the Journal Article Tag Suite, for example.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] An included CiteProc option allows pandoc to use bibliographic data from reference management software in any of five formats: BibTeX, BibLaTeX, CSL JSON or CSL YAML, or RIS.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] The information is automatically transformed into a citation in various styles (such as APA, Chicago, or MLA) using an implementation of the Citation Style Language.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] This allows the program to serve as a simpler alternative to LaTeX for producing academic writing in Markdown with inline citation keys.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] Or the program can be used to convert any bibliographic data stream in the accepted formats into a list of citations in a chosen style.
[src:pandoc/pandoc] The input format with the most support is Pandoc's extended version of Markdown.
